  "prompt": "Google Nexus 7: How to change default action for playing video from Engadget app? I have chosen YouTube but it doesn't play. My HTC One X uses streaming media player. How to change this default action to streaming media player?",
  "response": "Okay, let's troubleshoot how to change the default video player when opening videos from the Engadget app on your Nexus 7. Here's a breakdown of the steps and potential issues:\n\n**Understanding the Problem**\n\n*   **Default App Association:** Android has a mechanism for associating certain file types (like video files) with specific apps. When you first try to open a video, you're often presented with a choice of apps. If you select \"Always,\" that app becomes the default.\n*   **YouTube's Behavior:** While YouTube can play videos, it typically handles *YouTube* videos well. If the Engadget app is providing a link to a different video format or location (e.g., a direct MP4 file link, a different video hosting service), YouTube might not be the best choice.\n*   **HTC One X Streaming Media Player:** You're familiar with your HTC One X's streaming media player and how it works with the Engadget app.  That's what you're aiming for on your Nexus 7.\n\n**How to Clear the Existing YouTube Default Association**\n\n1.  **Go to Settings:** Open the \"Settings\" app on your Nexus 7.\n\n2.  **Find Apps:** Look for a section called \"Apps,\" \"Application Manager,\" or something similar. The exact wording varies slightly depending on the Android version.\n\n3.  **Locate the YouTube App:** Scroll through the list of installed apps and find \"YouTube.\"\n\n4.  **Open YouTube's App Info:** Tap on the \"YouTube\" app.\n\n5.  **Find \"Open by default\" or \"Set as default\":** Look for a section or setting related to \"Defaults,\" \"Open by default\", or \"Set as default\". Tap it.\n\n6.  **Clear Defaults:** You should see a button that says \"Clear Defaults\" or \"Clear Default Actions.\" Tap this button. This removes YouTube as the default for opening videos from Engadget.\n    *   **Important:** If you *don't* see a \"Clear Defaults\" button, it means YouTube hasn't actually been set as the default for that specific type of video link. This is possible, especially if Engadget uses a non-standard video URL format.  Skip down to the \"What to do if Clearing Defaults Doesn't Work\" section.\n\n**Installing a Suitable Streaming Media Player (if needed)**\n\nSince you mentioned your HTC One X uses a dedicated \"streaming media player,\" your Nexus 7 might not have one pre-installed that's as compatible with Engadget's video links. You might need to install one.\n\n1.  **Open the Google Play Store:** Find and open the Google Play Store app.\n\n2.  **Search for a Streaming Media Player:** Search for terms like:\n    *   \"Streaming media player\"\n    *   \"Video player\"\n    *   \"MP4 player\" (if you know the videos are MP4)\n    *   \"HLS player\" or \"M3U8 player\" (if the videos use HTTP Live Streaming)\n\n3.  **Choose a Player:**\n    *   **VLC for Android:** A popular, versatile player that supports many formats. (Highly recommended)\n    *   **MX Player:** Another excellent choice with good codec support.\n    *   **BSPlayer FREE:** Yet another good option.\n    *   Look for apps with good ratings and a large number of downloads.\n\n4.  **Install the Player:** Tap \"Install\" and follow the on-screen instructions.\n\n**Setting the New Default Video Player**\n\n1.  **Go back to the Engadget app:** Find an article with a video you want to play.\n\n2.  **Tap the Video Link:** Tap the video link as you normally would.\n\n3.  **Choose an App:** You should now see a dialog box asking you which app you want to use to open the video. *This is the crucial step.*\n\n4.  **Select Your Desired Media Player:** Choose the streaming media player you just installed (e.g., VLC, MX Player).\n\n5.  **Choose \"Always\":** Most importantly, select the \"Always\" option. This will set your chosen media player as the default for future videos from Engadget.\n\n**What to do if Clearing Defaults Doesn't Work (No \"Clear Defaults\" Button, or Still Opening with YouTube)**\n\nIf clearing defaults for YouTube *doesn't* solve the problem, it could mean one of these things:\n\n*   **Engadget App Uses a Different Handler:** The Engadget app might be directly configured to *always* open videos in YouTube, regardless of the system's default settings. This is less common, but possible.\n*   **The Video Link Type Isn't Associated:**  The specific type of link Engadget is using (e.g., a custom protocol or a Javascript redirect) might not be recognized by the Android system as a standard video file association.\n\nIf this is the case, here are some possible workarounds (less ideal, but they might work):\n\n1.  **Long-Press and \"Share\":** Instead of just tapping the video link in Engadget, try long-pressing it.  A menu might appear with a \"Share\" option. If so, tap \"Share\" and then choose your desired media player from the list of available apps. This might bypass Engadget's intended action.  This is a good test to see if the installed media player even *can* handle the video link.\n\n2.  **Copy the Link and Paste into Player:** If you can copy the video link (long-press, \"Copy link address\"), then open your media player (e.g., VLC) and look for an option to \"Open URL\" or \"Open Network Stream.\" Paste the link into the player.\n\n3.  **Contact Engadget Support:** As a last resort, contact Engadget's app developers (if possible) and ask if there's a setting within the app to control which video player is used. It's unlikely, but worth a try.\n\n4.  **Consider Alternative Engadget App/Website Access:** If the app is stubbornly refusing to use the correct player, consider using Engadget's website in Chrome (or another browser).  Websites typically respect the Android system's default video player settings more reliably.\n\n**Important Considerations**\n\n*   **Video Format Compatibility:** Make sure the streaming media player you choose supports the video format that Engadget uses (e.g., MP4, WebM, HLS/M3U8). VLC is generally good at handling most formats.\n*   **Network Connection:** Streaming video requires a stable internet connection (Wi-Fi or mobile data).\n*   **Codec Support:** Some video formats require specific codecs (software components that decode the video). Most popular media players come with a wide range of built-in codecs.\n\nBy following these steps, you should be able to regain control over which app opens videos from the Engadget app on your Nexus 7.  Good luck!\n",
